I didn’t know what to do. My mom came and got me. We went to a friend’s house, and then the news came on and I understood what was going on. The next day, we left for Florida.
 move to Florida 
The evacuation was mandatory, so my family had to leave my school and everything we owned behind. We had to leave in a hurry. We didn’t have time to bring more than the clothes we were wearing and a few things for the night. We didn’t know what would happen to our house or our pets. We left everything behind, and I didn’t see many of my friends for a long time.

He didn't know. He just knew he liked it. He had been in the study many times, but never sat in the chair behind the desk. He walked around it, looking at the pictures on the wall, and touching the leather of the chair. He had never sat in it, but he always felt like he should.
 move over, big boy, he thought. I'm sitting in your chair.

He walked around the chair, looking at it from all angles. He ran his hand along the arms, feeling the smoothness of the wood. He leaned his head back, feeling the weight of the chair against him. He sat down, and it felt just right.

He looked around the room, and suddenly he was no longer in the study. He was in a different room, a bedroom. He could hear the sounds of the city, and he could smell the sea. He looked around the room, and saw a bed, a nightstand, and a dresser. He could hear a man and a woman arguing in the other room.

"I don't like this place," the man was saying. "I want to go home."

"Don't be silly," the woman said. "This is your home now. You were born here, and this is where you will die. You will never feel more at home than you do right here."

The man started crying. "I don't want to die here. I want to go home."

The woman started crying too. "I'm sorry, but this is where you belong. You made a promise to the city, and you have to keep that promise."

The man started crying harder. "I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman started crying so hard she couldn't speak. She picked up a knife from the nightstand and held it to his throat. "If you ever say that again, I will cut your throat. Do you understand me?"

The man started crying even louder. "I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman put the knife down and started crying too. She walked over to the bed and sat down. "I'm sorry. I tried my best, but I couldn't save you. I'm so sorry."

The man walked over to the bed and sat down next to her. "I'm sorry too. I promise I'll be a good monster. I'll do whatever you want. Just don't kill me."

The woman smiled. "I wasn't going to kill you. I was going to turn you."

The man started crying again. "What? Turn me into what? A monster? I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman stood up and started walking around the room. "I know you don't want to be a monster, but you are. You are the monster that lives in the city. You are the monster that killed my husband. You are the monster that destroyed my life. You are the monster that has to stay here, in this city, with me, until the end of time."

The man started crying even louder. "I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman turned to the man. "I'm sorry, but you can't go home. You have to stay here. You have to stay with me."

The man started crying even louder. "I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman started crying so hard she couldn't speak. She picked up the knife and held it to his throat again. "If you ever say that again, I will cut your throat. Do you understand me?"

The man started crying even louder. "I don't want to be a monster. I want to go home."

The woman put the knife down and started crying even louder. She walked over to the dresser and started pulling things out of it. She walked back over to the man and started taking his clothes off. "Here, take these. You can use them to stay warm. They will help you forget about going home."

items.prompt: What does the Kroc Institute at Notre Dame focus on?
items.response:
Kroc Institute at Notre Dame research focuses on the social and cultural history of McDonald's. The Institute's research and public programming address a broad range of topics, including the company's cultural significance; the history of McDonald's architecture; the impact of McDonald's on American cities; the business practices of the McDonald's corporation; and the globalization of McDonald's.

The Institute's research and public programming are conducted by a team of scholars, including McDonald's historians, architects, urbanists, and cultural analysts. The Institute also hosts public programs that are open to the general public.

The Institute's research and public programming are supported by a variety of funding sources, including the McDonald's Corporation, the National Endowment for the Humanities, the Ford Foundation, and the National Science Foundation.

The Institute's research and public programming have been featured in a number of media outlets, including The New York Times, The Washington Post, CNN, and the BBC.

The Institute is named after Ray Kroc, the founder of McDonald's Corporation.

History
The Institute was founded in 2012 by the University of Notre Dame and the McDonald's Corporation. The Institute's founding director was Michael B. Miller, a professor of architecture and urban design at the University of Notre Dame. The Institute's founding vice director was Richard F. Sennett, a professor of sociology and director of the Center for the Study of Social Organization at the University of Notre Dame.

In 2013, the Institute launched a public program called "Architecture and the McDonald's Corporation." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored the architectural and urban design of McDonald's restaurants. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank.

In 2014, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and American Cities." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored the relationship between McDonald's restaurants and American urbanism. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame urbanist Richard R. Sisson.

In 2015, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and Globalization." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's role in the globalization of the fast food industry. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame sociologist Richard Sennett.

In 2016, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and the American Dream." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's role in American cultural mythology. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame historian Elizabeth A. Fenn.

In 2017, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and American Culture." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's cultural significance in American life. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame historian Elizabeth A. Fenn.

In 2018, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and the Environment." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's environmental impact. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame urbanist Richard Sennett.

In 2019, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and the Future." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's future as a company and as an industry. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame historian Elizabeth A. Fenn.

In 2020, the Institute launched a public program called "McDonald's and the Past." The program featured a series of public talks and events that explored McDonald's past as a company and as an industry. The program was organized by McDonald's historian Donald W. Shank and Notre Dame historian Elizabeth A. Fenn.

Funding
The Kroc Institute at Notre Dame is supported by a variety of funding sources, including the McDonald's Corporation, the National Endowment for the Humanities, the Ford Foundation, and the National Science Foundation.

Fermented grapes are known as wine!

Did you know that the first wine was made from grapes that had been fermented?

It’s true!

And it was made by the ancient Greeks!

But that’s not all!

The ancient Romans also made wine by fermenting grapes.

And red wine got its name because red grapes were used to make it!

But that’s not all!

In the 19th century, scientists discovered that if you left grapes to ferment for a long time, they would turn into something even better than wine!

They would turn into brandy!

items.prompt: What is a good result of losing weight?
items.response:
weight loss results

A:,

I'm not a doctor, but I've had success with weight loss by following a few simple rules. 

Don't skip meals. I used to think eating small meals frequently was a good way to control my calorie intake, but it turns out I was wrong.  I was eating too many calories and they were all at once.  I would get a "sugar high" and then crash, and the crash would be my hunger.  I would eat more and the weight would keep piling on.  I would eat less frequently, but more calories.  I finally figured this out by paying attention to the times I was most hungry.  Eating frequently throughout the day is a good way to maintain a healthy weight.
Exercise.  This is pretty obvious, but it's also important.  If you want to lose weight, you have to exercise more calories than you eat.  If you want to maintain your current weight, you need to exercise fewer calories than you eat.  If you want to lose weight, you need to exercise more calories than you eat.  I used to think I could just sit around all day and not do anything and not gain weight.  That's not true.  If you sit around all day, you will gain weight.  If you exercise regularly, you will maintain your current weight or even lose a little weight.  I've found that a 30 minute walk 4-5 times a day is enough to maintain my weight.
Eat real food.  I used to think I could eat whatever I wanted and still be healthy.  That's not true.  Eating real food and avoiding processed foods is the only way to have good nutrition and avoid eating too many calories.  Processed foods are full of sugar, salt, and chemicals.  They have very little nutritional value.  Eating real food and avoiding processed foods is the only way to have a healthy diet.
Don't look at the scale.  I used to weigh myself every day.  I would get discouraged if I gained a few pounds, and I would obsess about losing a few pounds.  I would try to force myself to eat less and exercise more to lose weight.  That didn't work.  I would get frustrated and give up.  I finally realized that the scale doesn't matter.  I don't weigh myself anymore.  I don't care how much I weigh.  I don't care if I lose weight or not.  I don't care if I eat healthy or not.  I just focus on having a good day.  If I eat well and exercise and have a good day, I will be happy.  If I have a bad day, I will still be happy.  I don't care what the scale says.  I don't look at the scale anymore.  I don't care what the scale says.  I just focus on my day and not the number on the scale.

A:

The best result of losing weight is feeling good about yourself.  Feeling good about yourself is not about the number on the scale.  It's about how you feel about yourself.  If you like the way you look and feel, then the number on the scale is just a happy by-product.

A:

I'm not a doctor either, but I've found that the best result of losing weight is not the number on the scale, but rather the feeling of accomplishment that comes from losing weight and feeling good about yourself.  I've found that the best way to keep the weight off is to focus on the feeling you get from losing weight, and not on the number on the scale.  I've found that the number on the scale can fluctuate a lot, and it's not really that important.  What is important is that you like the way you look and feel, and that you are happy with the progress you are making towards your goals.

items.prompt: Google Maps and other highway and street GPS services have replaced what?
items.response:
car phones, which were replaced by mobile phones, which were replaced by smartphones

A:

I would say that car GPSs were replaced by smartphones.
GPS stands for Global Positioning System.  A GPS device uses satellites in space to determine its location.  It can also use information from nearby cell towers to determine its approximate location to within a few miles.
A smartphone is a general purpose computer that runs a operating system such as Linux, Android, iOS, or Windows.  It can run applications downloaded from the app store.  It can also use GPS to determine its location.
A car with a GPS device can use GPS to determine its location when the car is not connected to a cell network.  However, when a car is connected to a cell network, the GPS device can use that information to determine its location more accurately.
